    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-12-30T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-12-30T21:00:00-05:00" n="841"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d841">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/799: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-31T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 31, 1931—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 31—2:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1158. Legation’s 1152, December 30, 1 p.m. Following from American Consul General
                    at Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“December 31, 10 a.m. [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>] My December 29, 8 p.m.
                            The following is the Chinese text of the mandate as it appears in
                            today’s issue of the semi-official <hi rend="italic">Chung Tang Jih
                                Pao:</hi>
                            <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>Regarding the application of jurisdiction over foreigners it is
                                    to be recalled that the regulations governing application of
                                    jurisdiction over foreigners in China in 12 articles were
                                    promulgated on May 4th and that it was decided upon to put them
                                    into force on and after January 1, 1932, as is on record.</p>
                                <p>Now due to the famine and calamities in various localities all
                                    necessary preparations have not as yet been effected. The
                                    enforcement of the said regulations governing application of
                                    jurisdiction over foreigners in China should be temporarily
                                    postponed. The appropriate authorities are still directed
                                    immediately and satisfactorily to complete all preparations in
                                    order that a date for enforcement may be fixed and judicial
                                    rights respected.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>Before dispatching my December 29, 8 p.m., I obtained oral confirmation
                            from an authoritative source.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
